      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always lock the trigger or remove the battery pack any time the tool is not in use.
      </div>

      <h3>Removing / inserting the battery</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Remove:</strong> push in the release buttons and pull the battery pack away from the tool.</li>
        <li><strong>Insert:</strong> slide the pack into the body of the tool until it latches securely into place.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Removing / installing the trigger caps</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery to avoid starting the tool.</li>
        <li>Push the lock switch to the locked position.</li>
        <li>Press the trigger cap release button and pull the trigger cap away from the tool.</li>
        <li>To reinstall, slide the trigger cap onto the tool. The bottom of the paddle-switch trigger
          cap sits flush in the pocket.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Attaching and removing accessories</h3>
      <div class="note">
        Use only square-drive sockets and accessories designed for impact tools. Other sockets can
        shatter or break, causing injury.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery to avoid starting the tool.</li>
        <li>To attach a socket, align it with the drive anvil and push it firmly onto the tool.</li>
        <li>To remove, pull the accessory straight off the drive anvil.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always wear eye protection marked to comply with ANSI&nbsp;Z87.1. In dusty conditions, use an
        OSHA-compliant dust extraction solution or wear appropriate respiratory protection.
      </div>

      <h3>Fuel gauge</h3>
      <p>Turn the tool on to check remaining charge &mdash; the fuel gauge lights for 2&ndash;3 seconds.</p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Indication</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1 light flashes 4 times</td><td>Less than 10% charge remaining</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1 light flashes 8 times, tool will not run</td><td>End of charge &mdash; recharge the battery pack</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lights flash, tool will not run</td><td>Battery too hot &mdash; allow it to cool down</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Forward / reverse shuttle</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Forward (clockwise):</strong> rotate the forward/reverse shuttle <em>counterclockwise</em>.</li>
        <li><strong>Reverse (counterclockwise):</strong> rotate the shuttle <em>clockwise</em>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Always check the direction of rotation before use.</p>

      <h3>Lock switch</h3>
      <p>
        Slide the lock switch to the locked position to disable the trigger; slide it to the unlocked
        position to enable it. The trigger will not work while the switch is locked. Always lock the
        trigger or remove the battery whenever the tool is not in use.
      </p>

      <h3>Starting, stopping, and speed control</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Grasp the handle firmly and pull the trigger to start. An LED turns on while the trigger is
          pulled and goes off shortly after release.</li>
        <li>Vary the speed with trigger pressure &mdash; the further it is pulled, the greater the speed.</li>
        <li>Release the trigger to stop. Make sure the tool has come to a complete stop before laying
          it down.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Remove the battery pack before performing any maintenance. Never disassemble the battery pack,
        charger, or tool except as described in these instructions.
      </div>

      <h3>General upkeep</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Adopt a regular maintenance program. Inspect for undue noise, misalignment or binding of
          moving parts, broken parts, or any other condition affecting operation.</li>
        <li>If the tool will not start or run at full power with a charged pack, clean the contacts on
          the battery pack. If it still misbehaves, return it to a Milwaukee service facility.</li>
        <li>Have an authorized service facility periodically inspect and maintain the tool, battery,
          and charger.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Greasing port (optional)</h3>
      <p>Use lithium-based grease. Lubricate after heavy use.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery to avoid starting the tool.</li>
        <li>For best results, point the anvil retention ball directly away from the trigger (facing upward).</li>
        <li>Apply grease through the fitting in the forward/reverse knob with a grease applicator for
          flush-type fittings, until fresh grease is visible.</li>
        <li>Wipe away excess grease.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Cleaning</h3>
      <div class="note">
        Never immerse the tool, battery pack, or charger in liquid or allow liquid to flow inside them.
      </div>
      <ul>
        <li>Clear dust and debris from any vents. Keep the tool dry and free of oil and grease.</li>
        <li>Clean with mild soap and a damp cloth only. Avoid gasoline, turpentine, lacquer/paint
          thinner, chlorinated solvents, ammonia, and ammonia-based detergents &mdash; they damage
          plastics and insulation.</li>
        <li>Never use flammable or combustible solvents around the tool.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause &amp; remedy</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Tool will not run; one fuel-gauge light flashes 8 times</td>
            <td>Battery is depleted &mdash; recharge the M12&trade; pack.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Tool will not run; fuel-gauge lights flash</td>
            <td>Battery pack is too hot &mdash; let it cool before use.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Trigger does nothing</td>
            <td>Lock switch is in the locked position &mdash; slide it to unlocked.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Will not start or runs weak on a fully charged pack</td>
            <td>Dirty contacts &mdash; clean the battery pack contacts. If it persists, return to a
              Milwaukee service facility.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Socket shatters or will not stay seated</td>
            <td>Wrong socket type &mdash; use only impact-rated square-drive sockets pushed firmly onto
              the anvil.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Ratchet feels rough or notchy</td>
            <td>Needs lubrication after heavy use &mdash; apply lithium grease through the greasing port.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

